# Why Data Matters So Much

To understand why data is important, we must first understand how Machine Learning actually works.

Many beginners imagine a model as a giant database of knowledge.

This is not true.

A machine learning model does not memorize facts in the way humans do.

Instead, it learns patterns.

Suppose we show a model the following dataset:

| House Size | Price    |
| ---------- | -------- |
| 1000 sq ft | ₹20 Lakh |
| 1500 sq ft | ₹30 Lakh |
| 2000 sq ft | ₹40 Lakh |

After seeing thousands of examples, the model begins recognizing a relationship between size and price.

It discovers:

```text
Larger House
     ↓
Higher Price
```

This relationship is learned from data.

Not from intelligence.

Not from reasoning.

Not from common sense.

Only from examples.

This means the quality of those examples determines the quality of the learned pattern.

---

# What Happens When Data Is Wrong?

Consider a modified dataset.

| House Size | Price      |
| ---------- | ---------- |
| 1000 sq ft | ₹20 Lakh   |
| 1500 sq ft | ₹30 Lakh   |
| 2000 sq ft | ₹40 Lakh   |
| 2100 sq ft | ₹8 Crore ❌ |

The last value is clearly incorrect.

Perhaps someone entered the wrong number.

Perhaps the data became corrupted.

Perhaps there was a typing mistake.

To a human, the error is obvious.

To a machine?

It looks perfectly valid.

The model now learns a distorted relationship.

As a result, future predictions become inaccurate.

This illustrates a critical principle:

> The model cannot distinguish truth from error. It only sees data.

